      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Read all safety warnings, instructions, illustrations and specifications provided with this power tool. Failure to follow them may result in electric shock, fire, and/or serious injury. Save all warnings and instructions for future reference.
      </div>

      <h3>Router-specific rules</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Hold the tool by the insulated gripping surfaces</strong> when the bit may contact hidden wiring. A live wire will energize exposed metal parts and shock the operator.</li>
        <li><strong>Clamp the workpiece</strong> to a stable platform. Holding work by hand or against your body leaves it unstable and can cause loss of control.</li>
        <li><strong>Do not cut metal.</strong> Always make sure the work surface is free of nails and foreign objects &mdash; cutting into a nail can make the bit and tool jump.</li>
        <li>Maintain a <strong>firm grip with both hands</strong> to resist starting torque.</li>
        <li>Keep hands away from the cutting area above and below the base. Never reach under the workpiece. Keep the base firmly on the work while cutting.</li>
        <li><strong>Never run the motor unit unless it is inserted in one of the bases</strong> &mdash; the motor is not designed to be handheld.</li>
        <li>Use sharp bits with a <strong>1/4&Prime; (6.4&nbsp;mm) shank</strong>; do not exceed a <strong>1-3/8&Prime; (34.9&nbsp;mm) cutting diameter</strong>. Follow the bit maker&rsquo;s speed recommendations.</li>
        <li>Be sure the motor has <strong>stopped completely</strong> before setting the router down, and that the bit is clear of the work before starting.</li>
        <li><strong>Always remove the battery pack</strong> before changing bits or making adjustments.</li>
        <li>Avoid <strong>climb-cutting</strong> (cutting in the opposite direction shown in Fig.&nbsp;Q). It increases the chance of losing control.</li>
        <li>Do not press the spindle lock while the motor is running &mdash; it can damage the spindle lock. <strong>Not recommended for use in a router table.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Never touch the bit immediately after use</strong> &mdash; it may be extremely hot.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        Always wear ANSI&nbsp;Z87.1 eye protection, ANSI&nbsp;S12.6 hearing protection, and NIOSH/OSHA-approved respiratory protection. Some routing dust (lead paint, silica, treated lumber) contains chemicals known to cause cancer or reproductive harm &mdash; work in a ventilated area with dust collection.
      </div>

