      <p><strong>Intended use:</strong> professional medium-duty routing. Do not use in wet conditions or near flammable liquids/gases, and do not use in a router table.</p>

      <h2>Battery</h2>

      <ul>
        <li>The battery pack ships partially charged &mdash; <strong>charge it fully before first use</strong> in a designated DeWALT charger.</li>
        <li>To install: align the pack with the rails inside the tool handle and slide it in until it seats firmly. To remove: press the release button and pull the pack out.</li>
        <li>A three-LED fuel gauge (press and hold to read) shows approximate remaining charge: 3&nbsp;LEDs = 75&ndash;100%, 2&nbsp;LEDs = 51&ndash;74%, 1&nbsp;LED = under&nbsp;50%.</li>
        <li>Best charging temperature is 65&ndash;75&nbsp;&deg;F (18&ndash;24&nbsp;&deg;C). Do not charge below 40&nbsp;&deg;F or above 104&nbsp;&deg;F. An Electronic Protection System shuts the tool off on overload, overheat, or deep discharge.</li>
        <li>Store packs in a cool, dry place, out of the charger, not fully depleted, and never with the trigger taped on.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Installing and Removing a Bit</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Projectile hazard. Only use bits whose shank matches the installed collet (1/4&Prime;). Never tighten the collet without a bit installed &mdash; even hand-tightening an empty collet can damage it. Always remove the battery first.
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove the motor unit from the base.</li>
        <li>Clean the bit, then insert its round shank fully into the loosened collet and pull it back out about 1/16&Prime; (1.6&nbsp;mm).</li>
        <li>Depress the spindle lock button (7) and turn the collet nut clockwise with the supplied wrench to tighten. Tighten securely so the bit cannot slip.</li>
        <li>For more torque, use the <strong>manual ratchet method</strong>: with the wrench still on the nut, release the spindle lock, reverse the wrench to reset its position, depress the lock again, and turn clockwise. Repeat until tight.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>To remove a bit, reverse the procedure, turning the collet nut counterclockwise. <strong>Plunge base only:</strong> keep the wrenches clear of the plunge rods &mdash; damaged rods restrict the plunge action.</p>
      <p>To change collet sizes, unscrew the whole collet assembly and install the desired one. The collet and collet nut are connected; do not try to separate them.</p>

      <h2>Fixed Base Setup &amp; Depth of Cut</h2>

      <div class="image-row">
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcw600/p13_figK.png" alt="Fig. K showing the motor unit aligned over the fixed base, with the two quick-release tabs (21) and the locking lever (12) called out" />
          <figcaption>Fig. K &mdash; inserting the motor into the fixed base</figcaption>
        </div>
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcw600/p14_figL.png" alt="Fig. L showing the fixed base depth adjustment ring (5), micro-adjustment scale (11), and locking lever (12)" />
          <figcaption>Fig. L &mdash; depth adjustment ring, micro-scale, and locking lever</figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Open the locking lever (12) on the base.</li>
        <li>Thread the depth adjustment ring (5) onto the motor to roughly mid-height, then insert the motor by aligning a guide-pin groove (9) with the base guide pins (17). Slide it down until the ring snaps into place.</li>
        <li>Open the locking lever and turn the ring until the bit just touches the workpiece. <strong>Clockwise raises</strong> the cutting head; <strong>counterclockwise lowers</strong> it.</li>
        <li>Turn the micro-adjustment scale (11) until its 0 lines up with the pointer on the bottom of the ring.</li>
        <li>Turn the ring until the pointer reaches the desired depth on the scale. Each mark = 0.015&Prime; (0.4&nbsp;mm); one full turn = 0.5&Prime; (12.7&nbsp;mm).</li>
        <li>Close the locking lever to lock the base.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>To remove the motor: remove the battery, open the locking lever, squeeze both quick-release tabs (21), and pull the motor from the base.</p>

      <h2>Plunge Base Setup &amp; Depth</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcw600/p14_figM.png" alt="Fig. M showing the plunge base with the depth adjustment rod (15), turret stop (14), thumb screw (40), zero adjuster tab (41), depth scale (42), and fine-adjustment knurled knob (43)" />
        <figcaption>Fig. M &mdash; plunge base depth rod, turret stop, and fine-adjustment knob</figcaption>
      </div>

      <div class="warning">
        Do not change the turret stop while the router is running &mdash; it puts your hands too near the cutter. Always tighten the travel-limiting nuts together, and set them so the bit can fully retract clear of the workpiece. Never adjust or remove the stop nut; the motor could disengage and cause loss of control.
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove the depth adjustment ring (5) from the motor &mdash; it is not used with the plunge base (snap it onto the fixed base for storage).</li>
        <li>Open the plunge base locking lever (39). With the spindle lock button facing front, align a motor groove with the guide pins (17) and slide the motor down to the motor stop (19). Close the lever.</li>
        <li>Pull down the plunge lock lever (16), push the handles down until the bit just touches the work, then release the lever to lock.</li>
        <li>Loosen the depth rod thumb screw (40), slide the depth rod (15) down to the lowest turret stop (14), and set the zero adjuster tab (41) to 0 on the depth scale (42).</li>
        <li>Slide the rod up so the tab aligns with the desired depth, then tighten the thumb screw.</li>
      </ol>
      <p><strong>Stepped (multi-pass) cuts:</strong> rotate the turret so the rod meets a taller stop first, then step down to shorter stops on each pass until final depth. <strong>Fine adjustment:</strong> the knurled knob (43) trims depth by about 1&nbsp;mm per turn &mdash; clockwise decreases depth, counterclockwise increases it (viewed from the top).</p>

      <h2>Accessories &amp; Attachments</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Subbases:</strong> the round subbase accepts universal template guides; the D-shaped subbase does not, and accommodates bits up to 1-3/8&Prime; (34.9&nbsp;mm). Use the optional centering tool (cone + pin) when changing or replacing a subbase.</li>
        <li><strong>Edge guides:</strong> fixed-base edge guide (DNP618) and premium/plunge edge guide (DW6913) are available separately.</li>
        <li><strong>Dust extraction:</strong> attachments mount to both the fixed and plunge bases (model-dependent); ensure the hose and collector are stable and clear of the work.</li>
        <li>Use only DeWALT-recommended accessories &mdash; others have not been tested with this tool.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Hand position:</strong> with the fixed base, place one hand on top of the battery and the other around the base. With the plunge base, grip both side handles (18) firmly.</li>
        <li><strong>Start/stop:</strong> press the &ldquo;I&rdquo; side of the dust-protected switch (3) to start; press the &ldquo;O&rdquo; side to stop. Clear the work area first and hold firmly to resist starting torque. Let the motor stop completely before setting the router down.</li>
        <li><strong>Plunge cutting:</strong> turn the router on first. Depress the plunge lock lever (16), plunge to the set depth, release the lever (this automatically locks the motor), make the cut, then depress the lever again to retract and turn off.</li>
        <li><strong>Soft start &amp; speed feedback:</strong> electronics minimize start-up torque and hold speed under load. If you load the motor and don&rsquo;t hear it slow down, reduce depth of cut or feed rate to avoid overheating.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Direction of Feed</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcw600/p16_figQ.png" alt="Fig. Q showing the correct feed sequence around the outside edge of a board: arrows numbered 1 through 4 indicating the router travels counterclockwise around an outside cut" />
        <figcaption>Fig. Q &mdash; correct feed direction for shaping an outside edge (steps 1&ndash;4)</figcaption>
      </div>
      <p>Always feed the router <em>against</em> the bit&rsquo;s rotation. As a rule, move <strong>counterclockwise on an outside cut</strong> and <strong>clockwise on an inside cut</strong>. To shape the outside edge of stock: (1)&nbsp;cut the end grain left to right, (2)&nbsp;the straight-grain side left to right, (3)&nbsp;the other end grain, then (4)&nbsp;the remaining straight-grain edge. Make several light passes rather than one heavy pass.</p>

      <h3>Choosing Router Speed</h3>
      <p>Turn the variable speed dial (4) to set speed. The router has 7 speeds from 16,000 to 25,500&nbsp;RPM.</p>
